First locate 2026 in the spiral.

Each “square layer’’ k (k = 0, 1, 2, …) contains the numbers  
(2k – 1)² + 1 up to (2k + 1)² and has side length 2k + 1.  
Its greatest number, (2k + 1)², is at the bottom-right corner (k , –k).

1. Which layer does 2026 belong to?  
√2026 ≈ 45.01.  
The next larger odd square is 47² = 2209, so 2026 lies in layer k = (47 – 1)/2 = 23.

2. Offset of 2026 from the bottom-right corner of its layer:  
2209 – 2026 = 183.

One revolution around the layer consists of four runs of 2k = 46 steps
(bottom, left, top, right edges), i.e. offsets

0 … 46 … 92 … 138 … 184 .

Offset 183 is on the “right edge’’ (the last but one step before reaching the
bottom-right corner again), so 2026 is one square above that corner:

Coordinate of 2026 : (23 , –22).

3. Coordinates of the eight neighbours

(NW) (22 , –21) (N) (23 , –21) (NE) (24 , –21)  
(W ) (22 , –22)          (E ) (24 , –22)  
(SW) (22 , –23) (S) (23 , –23) (SE) (24 , –23)

4. Value at an arbitrary coordinate (x , y)

Let k = max(|x|, |y|), m = (2k + 1)², L = 2k.

Bottom (y = –k) : n = m – (k – x)  
Left   (x = –k)  : n = m – 2k – (y + k)  
Top    (y =  k)  : n = m – 4k – (x + k)  
Right  (x =  k)  : n = m – 6k – (k – y)

Using the appropriate formula for every neighbour gives

(22 , –21)  k=22  → 1850  
(23 , –21)  k=23  → 2027  
(24 , –21)  k=24  → 2212  
(22 , –22)  k=22  → 2025  
(24 , –22)  k=24  → 2211  
(22 , –23)  k=23  → 2208  
(23 , –23)  k=23  → 2209  
(24 , –23)  k=24  → 2210

5. Sum of the eight neighbours

1850 + 2027 + 2212 + 2025 + 2211 + 2208 + 2209 + 2210 = 16 952.

Answer: 16 952
